deck: Tite Kubo is the creator of such popular manga series as 'Bleach' and 'Zombie Powder'
description:
Tite Kubo is the creator of both Bleach and Zombie Powder through Shueisha publication.

At the end of several Bleach Volumes Tite Kubo would make character profiles for several of the main characters in the series.

In the profiles Tite Kubo usually adds such remarks as Theme Songs, People they look up to and a break down of the character's personal stats, including height, weight, and date of birth.

Tite Kubo eventually had his series Bleach turned into an anime series which made it's way to the US and other several countries.
name: Tite Kubo

deck: Zeb Wells is a comic book writer primarily known for his work at Marvel, and his television work on the series Robot Chicken.
description:
Zeb Wells is a writer and filmmaker fairly new to the scene but who has garnered a great deal of respect from fans and other creators alike. He became famous for his work on Spider-Man and related characters in the early 2000s (such as Doctor Octopus: Year One), and has continued to gain popularity ever since. Although a great deal of his work has been done for Marvel characters, he has also been the writer for other titles, including at the fledgling Virgin Comics. 

In addition to Zeb's work on vairous Spider-Man titles, his work at Marvel includes the Young Avengers/Runaways tie-in to the Civil War event, th e Elektra tie-in to the Dark Reign storyline, and Venom: Dark Origin, which retells the encounter between Eddie Brock and the alien symbiote. 

His work for television and film includes the hit TV series Robot Chicken, for which he has won an Annie Award. Currently, Zeb Wells has an exclusive writing contract with Marvel.
name: Zeb Wells

deck: A consummate artist whose comic work began with Virgin Comics.
description: Mukesh Singh is an artist foremost and a comics artist second. Singh has been an avid fan of comics his entire life, having found a Superman title in a rummage bin when he was a boy living in India. Though he has waited until now to put his talents and passion toward benefiting the comics community, Singh has been in graphic design and illustration for years. He began his career as a comics artist at Virgin Comics on their Devi title, and has expanded his resume from there. He counts artists as varied as Gil Kane, Mike Mignola, and Leinil Francis Yu among his inspirations.
name: Mukesh Singh

deck: He is an artist who is as versatile as he is distinct, having worked in such varied fields as theatre, animation, and toy box art (aside from his comics work). Currently he is illustrating Superman.  He will illustrate Teen Titans (vol. 5) starting July 2014.
description:
Career

Kenneth Rocafort started his career in comics in 2005 when he took over artistic duties for the Hunter-Killer series published by Top Cow. Two years later, in 2007 he drew the Madame Mirage series -- also for Top Cow. He stayed true to this publisher and worked on Cyberforce/Hunter-Killer with Mark Waid, his first collaborator in comics.

Rocafort recently collaborated with writer Ron Marz on the most recent Top Cow Pilot Season winner, Velocity.

Rocafort's first work for DC comics was working with writer Paul Cornell on Action Comics. With the launch of DC's The New 52, he illustrated the first year of Red Hood and the Outlaws, and has now joined Red Hood writer, Scott Lobdell, on Superman starting with the #0 issue.
name: Kenneth Rocafort

deck: Former Talent Liaison for Marvel Entertainement, he's the current Senior Vice President, Creator and Content Developer.
description:
As the Talent Liaison for Marvel, his main responsibility included scouting new artistic talent for the company, often times requiring him to travel to comic conventions around the world to meet possible candidates and review their work. He also frequently tweets numerous advice to new creators on his Twitter account. 
 
Cebulski’s title as the SVP, Creator and Content Development expands his role in terms of searching for new talent. According to Marvel.com, he will also “advise on creative directions for Marvel's key titles” and “work on creative aspects of development of larger corporate initiatives.”

Cebulski is also a noted former editor and writer who worked on various comic titles including “Marvel Mangaverse,” "Loners," and "X-Infernus." He also wrote "Wonderlost" – an anthological book containing short autobiographical stories based on his early high school years.  
 
As a self-proclaimed foodie, Cebulski appeared as a guest judge on Food Network’s Challenge Show on the episode entitled, “Extreme Villain Cakes.” It first aired on April 11, 2010.
name: C.B. Cebulski

He has designed many inventions, including models of parachutes, self-propelled carts, tanks, flying vehicles and even conceived some ideas that were way ahead of his time, like a calculator, a robot and the use of concentrated solar power.

deck: A writer/artist for Virgin Comics, Siddarth Kotian is an internationally published comic book artist and writer from Mumbai, India. His published works include the Graphic Novel Eat the Dead, sci fi mini series The Stranded and others...
description:
Siddharth Kotian is one of the leading creative members of Virgin comics since its launch in 2006. He wrote the Virgin flagship title Devi creating the entire architecture and characters of the series. Curiously Siddharth left the Devi series after just two issues. He did not appear on the scene again until the late 2007 one shot horror comic 'Eat the Dead' which was written and drawn by him. Eat the Dead is a stylistically rendered and painstakingly detailed comic which dealt with the Indian 'dark sadhus' called Aghoris. It is said to be one of the best horror comics around but has not shot into mainstream prominence.

Siddharth Kotian's latest work was on The Stranded (2008) written by Mike Carey (Lucifer, X-men). His art style changed in this comic and the first two issues featured average art but issue #3 saw him finding his ground. The series is still going on.

Siddharth Kotian currently resides in Bombay, India.
name: Siddharth Kotian

deck: Best known for the creation of Wonder Woman, he was also a psychologist and inventor of the lie detector.
description:
William Moulton Marston created Wonder Woman during World War II in a reaction to what he saw as a DC Universe dominated by male characters such as Superman and Batman. Then came heroes such as Marvel's Captain America who were created as a largely patriotic reaction to the Axis forces of WWII. Marston wanted a super heroine to even the battlefield.

"He was inventing somebody like that new Superman fellow, only his character would promote a global psychic revolution by forsaking Biff! Bam! and Ka-Runch! for The Power of Love. Well," said Mrs. Marston, who was born liberated, "this super-hero had better be a woman."

- NYTimes

Based on his wife and Olive Byrne, Moulton Marston had created one of DC's flagship superheroes and its first female heroine, Wonder Woman.
